<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="2337" pageId="4" pageNumber="2333" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[138,1184,1629,1685]" lastBlockId="5.[125,1173,1408,1685]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="2334" pageId="4" pageNumber="2333">
<emphasis box="[138,225,1629,1653]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="2333">Female.</emphasis>
Body dark green with coppery tints. Scape infuscate with ventral edge testaceous; pedicel dark brown, faintly metallic; flagellum brown. Legs with coxae concolorous with thorax; femora and tibiae bright testaceous, pro- and mesofemora brown on posterior surfaces in basal halves; all tibiae broadly brown on posterior surfaces; tarsi brown. Wings clear; tegulae, and parastigma, stigma and postmarginal veins brown, remainder of venation stramineous. Length 
<quantity box="[482,574,1597,1621]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="5" pageNumber="2334" unit="mm" value="2.4">2.4 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4581596" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4581596" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4581596/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="2334" startId="5.[125,185,1408,1427]" targetBox="[170,1127,133,1372]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[125,1173,1408,1685]" pageId="5" pageNumber="2334">
Figure 2. 
<emphasis box="[221,372,1408,1427]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="2334">
Riυasia 
<taxonomicName authority="Askew &amp; Nieves-Aldrey, 2005" authorityName="Askew &amp; Nieves-Aldrey" authorityYear="2005" box="[295,372,1408,1427]" class="Insecta" family="Pteromalidae" genus="Ricasia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="2334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fumariae" status="sp. n.">fumariae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[379,431,1408,1427]" pageId="5" pageNumber="2334" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(A) Adult metasoma in ventral view; (B) mesosoma in posterodorsal view; (C) fore wing; (D) fully grown larva in ventral view; (E) fully grown larva, head in anterior view; (F) fully grown larva, oral region.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="5.[125,1173,1408,1685]" lastBlockId="7.[125,1172,137,1102]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="2336" pageId="5" pageNumber="2334">
Head with vertex, face and clypeus very finely reticulate, the small areoles separated by relatively deeply engraved lines, and with numerous small piliferous punctures. Head in dorsal view 1.1X as broad as mesoscutum, 2.1X as broad as long; temples slightly over half eye length; frons scarcely advanced in front of eyes, almost straight; POL about 2.0X OOL, posterior ocellus separated from eye by about 2X its diameter; eye with very short, inconspicuous hairs. Head (
<figureCitation box="[480,597,1406,1430]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="4.[138,198,1416,1435]" captionTargetBox="[183,1140,133,1380]" captionTargetId="figure-33@4.[183,1140,133,1380]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 1. Riυasia fumariae sp. n., adult female. (A) Antenna; (B) detail of antennal clava; (C) head in anterior view; (D) head in posterior view; (E) mesosoma in dorsal view; (F) mesosoma in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4581594" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4581594/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="2335">Figure 1C</figureCitation>
) in front view 1.44X as broad as high; vertex convex; inner eye margins slightly divergent ventrad, minimum (dorsal) separation 1.36X height of eye; gena gently curved; malar space 0.38X height of eye; mouth opening broad, more than 3X malar space; clypeus with anterior margin slightly recessed, very weakly concave; torulus with lower margin about level with bottom of eye and separated from upper margin of clypeus by only its diameter; antennal scrobes shallow, short, extending less than half distance between torulus and anterior ocellus, no interantennal prominence. Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[256,373,1629,1653]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="4.[138,198,1416,1435]" captionTargetBox="[183,1140,133,1380]" captionTargetId="figure-33@4.[183,1140,133,1380]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 1. Riυasia fumariae sp. n., adult female. (A) Antenna; (B) detail of antennal clava; (C) head in anterior view; (D) head in posterior view; (E) mesosoma in dorsal view; (F) mesosoma in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4581594" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4581594/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="2335">Figure 1A</figureCitation>
) with scape short, 4.3X as long as broad, not quite reaching lower margin of anterior ocellus; anellus plus first funicle segment almost as long as pedicel; flagellum not clavate, broadening only slightly distally, all segments at least slightly broader than long, each with a single, transverse row of linear sensilla, clava (
<figureCitation box="[948,1063,169,193]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="4.[138,198,1416,1435]" captionTargetBox="[183,1140,133,1380]" captionTargetId="figure-33@4.[183,1140,133,1380]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 1. Riυasia fumariae sp. n., adult female. (A) Antenna; (B) detail of antennal clava; (C) head in anterior view; (D) head in posterior view; (E) mesosoma in dorsal view; (F) mesosoma in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4581594" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4581594/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="2336">Figure 1B</figureCitation>
) with an apical tuft of two 
<typeStatus box="[335,394,201,225]" pageId="7" pageNumber="2336">types</typeStatus>
of hair, one fine and bent, the other stout and weakly curved.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4581600" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4581600" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4581600/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="2335" startId="6.[138,198,1232,1251]" targetBox="[183,1140,133,1196]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[138,1185,1232,1277]" pageId="6" pageNumber="2335">
Figure 3. 
<emphasis box="[233,382,1232,1251]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="2335">
Riυasia 
<taxonomicName authority="Askew &amp; Nieves-Aldrey, 2005" authorityName="Askew &amp; Nieves-Aldrey" authorityYear="2005" box="[305,382,1232,1251]" class="Insecta" family="Pteromalidae" genus="Ricasia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="2335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fumariae" status="sp. n.">fumariae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[387,438,1232,1251]" pageId="6" pageNumber="2335" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(A) Larva, left mandible; (B) larva, right mandible; (C) final instar larva 
<emphasis box="[1108,1161,1232,1251]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="2335">in situ</emphasis>
in gall of 
<emphasis box="[203,362,1258,1277]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="2335">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nieves-Aldrey" authorityYear="1994" box="[203,276,1258,1277]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Neaylax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="2335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Neaylax</taxonomicName>
υersicolor
</emphasis>
; (D) pupa 
<emphasis box="[469,523,1258,1277]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="2335">in situ</emphasis>
; (E) late pupa 
<emphasis box="[668,722,1258,1277]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="2335">in situ</emphasis>
; (F) adult just after emerging from pupa.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="7.[125,1172,137,1102]" pageId="7" pageNumber="2336">
Thorax with dorsal sculpture similar to that of vertex, with very fine, engraved reticulation and many small piliferous punctures. Mesosoma in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[1047,1162,267,291]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="4.[138,198,1416,1435]" captionTargetBox="[183,1140,133,1380]" captionTargetId="figure-33@4.[183,1140,133,1380]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 1. Riυasia fumariae sp. n., adult female. (A) Antenna; (B) detail of antennal clava; (C) head in anterior view; (D) head in posterior view; (E) mesosoma in dorsal view; (F) mesosoma in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4581594" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4581594/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="2336">Figure 1E</figureCitation>
) 1.7X as long as broad; pronotum 2X as broad as long, campaniform, sloping from posterior margin to neck without indication of a collar; mesoscutum medially about as long as scutellum, 2X as broad as long; scutellum about as broad as long, broadly based with scutello-axillar sutures not strongly convergent, meeting hind margin of mesoscutum only slightly mesad of notauli, a deep groove separating midlobe of mesoscutum from scutellum; frenum with sculpture similar to that of remainder of scutellum, the frenal groove weakly impressed; dorsellum slightly shorter than frenum and with similar sculpture. Mesosoma in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[276,391,526,550]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="4.[138,198,1416,1435]" captionTargetBox="[183,1140,133,1380]" captionTargetId="figure-33@4.[183,1140,133,1380]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 1. Riυasia fumariae sp. n., adult female. (A) Antenna; (B) detail of antennal clava; (C) head in anterior view; (D) head in posterior view; (E) mesosoma in dorsal view; (F) mesosoma in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4581594" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4581594/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="2336">Figure 1F</figureCitation>
) 2X as long as high, dorsal surface weakly convex; upper part of mesepisternum smooth. Hind leg with upper surface of coxa densely pilose; tibia with outer apical spur half as long as the inner which is a little longer than the apical breadth of the tibia. Propodeum (
<figureCitation box="[347,464,623,647]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="5.[125,185,1408,1427]" captionTargetBox="[170,1127,133,1372]" captionTargetId="figure-69@5.[170,1127,133,1372]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 2. Riυasia fumariae sp. n. (A) Adult metasoma in ventral view; (B) mesosoma in posterodorsal view; (C) fore wing; (D) fully grown larva in ventral view; (E) fully grown larva, head in anterior view; (F) fully grown larva, oral region." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4581596" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4581596/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="2336">Figure 2B</figureCitation>
) medially 0.36X length of scutellum; median carina weakly raised and irregular; lateral plicae indicated only at the hind margin of propodeum; median area with fine, weakly raised reticulation which tends to form irregular carinulae running obliquely from median carina; spiracle separated from anterior edge of propodeum by about two diameters and scarcely closer to metanotum than to supracoxal flange; callus quite thickly pilose; nucha short.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[125,1172,137,1102]" pageId="7" pageNumber="2336">
Fore wing (
<figureCitation box="[287,408,818,842]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="5.[125,185,1408,1427]" captionTargetBox="[170,1127,133,1372]" captionTargetId="figure-69@5.[170,1127,133,1372]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 2. Riυasia fumariae sp. n. (A) Adult metasoma in ventral view; (B) mesosoma in posterodorsal view; (C) fore wing; (D) fully grown larva in ventral view; (E) fully grown larva, head in anterior view; (F) fully grown larva, oral region." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4581596" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4581596/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="2336">Figure 2C</figureCitation>
), basal cell entirely pilose; speculum small, not extending behind marginal vein, separated from cubital vein by a broad band of hairs, and from parastigma by a narrow band; costal cell with submarginal hairs on its upper surface in distal half or more; ratio lengths of costal cell: marginal vein: stigmal vein: postmarginal vein as 106:35:29:54; stigmal vein slightly curved, stigma small, but with relatively long uncus, separated by about 3X its height from costal edge.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[125,1172,137,1102]" pageId="7" pageNumber="2336">
Petiole of gaster about 6X as broad as long, smooth. Gaster (
<figureCitation box="[873,991,1013,1037]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="5.[125,185,1408,1427]" captionTargetBox="[170,1127,133,1372]" captionTargetId="figure-69@5.[170,1127,133,1372]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 2. Riυasia fumariae sp. n. (A) Adult metasoma in ventral view; (B) mesosoma in posterodorsal view; (C) fore wing; (D) fully grown larva in ventral view; (E) fully grown larva, head in anterior view; (F) fully grown larva, oral region." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4581596" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4581596/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="2336">Figure 2A</figureCitation>
) sublanceolate, apically acute, almost 2X as long as broad, longer than rest of body (70:59); ovipositor sheath protruding only slightly; hypopygium with tip at 0.3X gaster length.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[125,1172,1142,1232]" pageId="7" pageNumber="2336">
<emphasis box="[125,191,1143,1167]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="2336">Male.</emphasis>
Closely resembles female but with antennal scape broader, 3.3X as long as broad, with a shiny boss extending over most of its anterior edge. Gaster obovate, 1.4X as long as broad, about as long as mesosoma, without ventral plica.
</paragraph>
